article.headline: New Mexico State 87, Hawaii 84
article.story: LAS CRUCES, N.M. (AP) -- Statistically, it was New Mexico State's best offensive performance of the season. Coach Reggie Theus, however, felt defense made the difference. Tyrone Nelson had 28 points and 11 rebounds while Elijah Ingram added 21 points and New Mexico State made 22 of 26 free throws in the second half during an 87-84 win over Hawaii on Saturday night. "I thought our intensity level was through the roof down the stretch," Theus said. "We had a lull there, but once we went to the trap, our energy level went up. Our defense helped our offense. We got a lot of layups." The Aggies (7-8, 3-1 WAC) shot 50 percent from the floor, 50 percent from 3-point range and 81 percent from the free throw line. New Mexico State also had a 34-26 rebounding advantage over the larger Warriors (8-6, 2-2). "Tonight, quickness beat size," Hawaii coach Riley Wallace said. "Their one-on-one offense was better than our one-on-one defense. They outrebounded us and every time we got a lead, we acted like we thought we were going to blow them out and started trying to run with them." Julian Sensley scored a career-high 32 points for Hawaii, which led by as many as 12 points at 61-49 with 14:24 remaining. But the Aggies used an 11-0 burst in less than two minutes to pull within 61-60. Sensley scored seven of his team's next nine points as the Warriors went ahead 70-62, but Hawaii -- which has lost 18 of its last 20 road games -- then failed to score over the next six minutes. "I kind of hit the wall late in the game," Sensley said. "They were able to take me off my game." The Aggies recaptured the lead and took command, with Nelson and forward David Fisher keying a 12-0 run, and New Mexico State turned to free throws down the stretch. Overall, the Aggies made 30-of-37 free throw attempts. "We'll be paying to watch Sensley play someday," Theus said. "But on this night, Tyrone had 28 and 11 and he was the best player on the floor." Fisher added 15 points for the Aggies and Mike Mitchell scored 11. "As a young coach, it's extremely gratifying to watch the growth of this team," Theus said. "They are starting to believe in themselves."
